FEATURISATION & MODEL TUNING¶

In [2]:
#  DOMAIN: Semiconductor manufacturing process

#  CONTEXT: A complex modern semiconductor manufacturing process is normally under constant surveillance via the monitoring of
# signals/variables collected from sensors and or process measurement points. However, not all of these signals are equally valuable in a
# specific monitoring system. The measured signals contain a combination of useful information, irrelevant information as well as noise.
# Engineers typically have a much larger number of signals than are actually required. If we consider each type of signal as a feature, then
# feature selection may be applied to identify the most relevant signals. The Process Engineers may then use these signals to determine key
# factors contributing to yield excursions downstream in the process. This will enable an increase in process throughput, decreased time to
# learning and reduce the per unit production costs. These signals can be used as features to predict the yield type. And by analysing and
# trying out different combinations of features, essential signals that are impacting the yield type can be identified.
#  DATA DESCRIPTION: sensor-data.csv : (1567, 592)
# The data consists of 1567 datapoints each with 591 features.
# The dataset presented in this case represents a selection of such features where each example represents a single production entity with
# associated measured features and the labels represent a simple pass/fail yield for in house line testing. 
# Target column  1 corresponds to a pass and 1 corresponds to a fail 
# and the data time stamp is for that specific test point.

#  PROJECT OBJECTIVE: We will build a classifier to predict the Pass/Fail yield of a particular process entity and analyse whether all the
# features are required to build the model or not.

Summary & Observations

  • The dataset has 1567 rows and 592 columns.
  • There are too many features available, we need to find the key contributing features and remove the non-contributing features for training.
  • The dataset contains null values, Not applicable values so we have to treat the data
  • The dataset has class imbalance hence we need to treat them
  • Data need to be scaled as it has different standard deviations across attributes
  • PCA can be applied for reducing the dimensionality
  • Correlation between attributes can be visualized and highly contributing column pairs can be examined and dropping atleast one.

#Using Pearson Correlation finding the highly correlated column pairs where which the first column can be removed leaving the other

def correlation(dataset, threshold):
    col_corr = set()  # Set of all the names of correlated columns
    corr_matrix = dataset.corr()
    for i in range(len(corr_matrix.columns)):
        for j in range(i):
            if abs(corr_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > threshold: # we are interested in absolute coeff value
                colname = corr_matrix.columns[i]  # getting the name of column
                col_corr.add(colname)
    return col_corr

In [36]:
# Remove outliers using IQR

for i in X_train.columns:
    q1, q2, q3 = X_train[i].quantile([0.25,0.5,0.75])
    IQR = q3 - q1
    a = X_train[i] > q3 + 1.5*IQR
    b = X_train[i] < q1 - 1.5*IQR
    X_train[i] = np.where(a | b, q2, X_train[i])

# Create a LogisticRegression model using Pipeline
pipeline_LR = Pipeline([
    ('scaler',StandardScaler()),
    ('clf', LogisticRegression())
])

pipeline_LR.fit(X_train_resampled,y_train_resampled)

y_predict = pipeline_LR.predict(X_test)
train_model_score = pipeline_LR.score(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)
test_model_score  = pipeline_LR.score(X_test, y_test)
tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_predict).ravel()
lr_recall = round(tp/(tp+fn), 3)   
lr_precision = round(tp/(tp+fp), 3)  
lr_specificity =round(tn/(tn+fp),3)    

result = pd.DataFrame({'Model' : ['Logistic Regression'],
                        'Training Acc' : [train_model_score],  
                        'Test Acc' : [test_model_score], 
                        'Precision' : [lr_precision],
                        'True positive rate' : [lr_recall], 
                        'True negative rate' : [lr_specificity],
                        'False positive rate' :  [1-lr_specificity]})
result

# Applying Randomized Search for Logistic Regression
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from scipy.stats import randint as sp_randint

# specify parameters and distributions to sample from
LR_param_dist = {"C": sp_randint(1, 6),
              "penalty": ["l1", "l2" ],
                }

# run randomized search
samples = 5 # number of random samples 
LR_randomCV = RandomizedSearchCV(lrcl, param_distributions=LR_param_dist, n_iter=samples,cv=3) 

LR_randomCV.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)
y_pred = LR_randomCV.predict(X_test)

train_model_score = LR_randomCV.best_score_
test_model_score = LR_randomCV.score(X_test,y_test)

print('Best Params for Logistic Rgression ',LR_randomCV.best_params_)
print('\n')

tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_predict).ravel()
lr_recall = round(tp/(tp+fn), 3)   
lr_precision = round(tp/(tp+fp), 3)  
lr_specificity =round(tn/(tn+fp),3)    

result.loc[7] = ['LogisticRegression Hypertuning', train_model_score, test_model_score,lr_precision,lr_recall,lr_specificity,1-lr_specificity]
result

# Applying Randomized Search for RandomForest
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from scipy.stats import randint as sp_randint

# build a classifier
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50)

# specify parameters and distributions to sample from
RF_param_dist = {"max_depth": [3, None],
              "max_features": sp_randint(5, 11),
              "min_samples_split": sp_randint(5, 11),
              "min_samples_leaf": sp_randint(5, 11),
              "criterion": ["gini", "entropy"]}

# run randomized search
samples = 5  # number of random samples 
RF_randomCV = RandomizedSearchCV(clf, param_distributions=RF_param_dist, n_iter=samples,cv=3) 

RF_randomCV.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)
y_pred=RF_randomCV.predict(X_test)

train_model_score = RF_randomCV.best_score_
test_model_score = RF_randomCV.score(X_test,y_test)

print('Best Params for Random Forest ',RF_randomCV.best_params_)
print('\n')

tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_predict).ravel()
lr_recall = round(tp/(tp+fn), 3)   
lr_precision = round(tp/(tp+fp), 3)  
lr_specificity =round(tn/(tn+fp),3)    

result.loc[9] = ['RandomForest Hypertuning', train_model_score, test_model_score,lr_precision,lr_recall,lr_specificity,1-lr_specificity]
result

Best Params for Random Forest  {'criterion': 'gini', 'max_depth': None, 'max_features': 5, 'min_samples_leaf': 7, 'min_samples_split': 10}

Conclusion¶

The provided dataset had 1567 rows and 592 features. After treating the missing values we have reduced the features to 560 features After removing the zero standard deviation features are reduced to 444. After removing the 90% correlated columns the features are reduced to 249. Target class imbalance was addressed using SMOTE method

Model Improvization: We have trainied the model using LogisticRegression, RandomForest, KNN, SVC and Gradient Boosting. But most of which resulted in overfitting. Hence hypertuned the models using randomized search where Random forest tuned out to yield 93% accuracy.
